ce:section.ce:para:
The synthesis route of polymer and carbon dots functionalized porphyrin based Zr-MOF photocatalyst is shown in Scheme 1. First, pre-synthesized CDs were encapsulated into the PCN-222 channels in solvothermal preparation process of MOF. And the catechol terminal groups of PNIPAM were skillfully functionalized to the PCN-222 through coordination interaction. Three catechol-capping thermo-sensitive polymers (PNIPAM1, PNIPAM2 and PNIPAM3) with different chain lengths were synthesized using typical RAFT polymerization by adjusting the ratio of [DA-CTA]: [AIBN]: [NIPAM]. The obtained polymers of PNIPAM1, PNIPAM2 and PNIPAM3 were analyzed by 1H NMR (Fig. 1
                        a). Three protons of C11H22CH3 appeared at 0.87 ppm (g). And chemical shifts of six protons, one proton in CH(CH3)2 and twenty-two protons in C11H22CH3 appeared at 4.0 (c) and 1.1 ppm (d), respectively. The proton signal at 6.4 ppm was attributed to the imino group (b). In addition, the chemical shifts of the protons in CHCH2 can be observed at 2.48–1.33 ppm. By comparing the integral area ratios g and c of each peak, the number of repeat units in PNIPAM1, PNIPAM2 and PNIPAM3 were calculated as 40, 94 and 140. The number-average molecular weights for the three polymers were obtained as 5000 and 11,100 and 16300, which correspond with the GPC results basically with a relative narrow polydispersity index (PDI) of 1.16, 1.27 and 1.19 (Fig. 1b, Table S1). The phase transition temperature of the synthesized PNIPAM2 was measured based on the transmittance change with temperature (Fig. S1-2
                        ). The phase transition of the PNIPAM2 was observed in the temperature range of 25–40 °C and the transmittance spectrum of PNIPAM2 had an obvious inflection point between 30 °C and 35 °C. The LCST of PNIPAM2 is around 33 °C determined by the temperature-dependent transmittance curve at 550 nm. The polymer dissolved well in water at temperature below the LCST, but above the LCST the polymer chain will curl. In fact, PNIPAM2 can act as a switch in the catalytic process [49]. P(PEGMA) and PMMA were also synthesized via RAFT polymerization in order to study the modification of catalysts by different polymers. The number-average molecular weights for P(PEGMA) and PMMA were obtained from their 1H NMR spectra (Fig. S3) as 9970 and 10060, which correspond with PNIPAM2 basically.

For 2N-CDs@PCN-222@PNIPAM, the PNIPAM was anchored to PCN-222 by formation of O-Zr-O bond through the catechol terminal groups of polymer chains. The extension of polymer chains in water enhanced the affinity of the photocatalyst to water molecules, thereby promoting the efficiency of photo-generated charge transfer between the 2N-CDs@PCN-222@PNIPAM and the target pollutant [45]. And the PNIPAM modified 2N-CDs@PCN-222 photocatalyst was more evenly dispersed in the water, and the degradation effect of pollutants was further improved (Fig. 6c). In particular, 2N-CDs@PCN-222@PNIPAM2, as a photocatalyst under visible light, can remove 98.4% of the RhB in 5 min, 99.5% in 10 min, and almost 100 % in 20 min. This phenomenon fully demonstrated the functional improvement of PNIPAM on PCN-222. Fig. 6d shows the kinetic study of the synthesized photocatalysts, and the corresponding apparent rate constants of 2N-CDs@PCN-222@PNIPAM2, 2N-CDs@PCN-222@PNIPAM1, 2N-CDs@PCN-222@PNIPAM3 and 2N-CDs@PCN-222 are 0.2556 min−1, 0.2426 min−1, 0.1763 min−1 and 0.1530 min−1, respectively. The excellent photocatalytic performance of 2N-CDs@PCN-222@PNIPAM2 is attributed to the appropriate polymer chain length and grafting density [66]. The limited graft space resulted in a decrease in the grafting density of the long polymer chains, while the short polymer chains issue in insufficient wettability of the photocatalyst. In addition, the influence of temperature on photocatalysis has also been explored (Fig. 7
                        a). The removal of the RhB was monitored between 25 and 40 °C. When the temperature was above the LCST of PNIPAM, the removal efficiency decreased by 34.47 % and 11.01 % at 10 min and 60 min, respectively. The extensive hydrogen bonds between water and PNIPAM enables the PNIPAM to be dissolved in water. However, the hydrogen bond will be disrupted when the temperature is higher than LCST. Instead, intra- and intermolecular hydrogen bonding/hydrophobic interactions formed by structural phase transition of PNIPAM dominate, thus forming a hydrophobic barrier that prevents the photocatalyst from contacting the pollutant [39]. Nevertheless, when the temperature below LCST of PNIPAM, this hydrophobic barrier disappears due to the recovery of the polymer chains (Fig. S13). This conclusion and the phase change morphology of the 2N-CDs@PCN-222@PNIPAM2 at high temperature further indicate that the polymer can act as a switch for photocatalytic reaction. In order to prove that the further improvement of photocatalyst effect is due to the hydrophilicity of polymer, we synthesized 2N-CDs@PCN-222@P(PEGMA) and 2N-CDs@PCN-222@PMMA under the same conditions. The number average molecular weights of PMMA (10060) and P(PEGMA) (9970) are similar to that PNIPAM2 on 2N-CDs@PCN-222, and the resulted PMMA and P(PEGMA) catalysts displayed similar level of BET surface area (Fig. S8). However, compared with 2N-CDs@PCN-222@PNIPAM2, the photocatalytic performance of 2N-CDs@PCN-222@PMMA is greatly reduced, while the removal efficiency of RhB by 2N-CDs@PCN-222@P(PEGMA) is excellent (Fig. 7b). We also studied the effects of different components in the ternary photocatalyst on the adsorption pollutants (Fig.S14). At the dark, when the adsorption and desorption of the RhB on the photocatalysts reached equilibrium, the PCN-222, 2N-CDs@PCN-222 and 2N-CDs@PCN-222@PNIPAM2 were separated and dispersed in DI water for 48 h, respectively. As shown in Fig. S14, UV–vis spectrum of adsorption and desorption of RhB in photocatalysts demonstrated that a large amount of the RhB were adsorbed in the photocatalyst under dark. After being exposed to visible light for 5 min, the photocatalyst was separated again and exchanged with deionized water. And, the adsorption of RhB by 2N-CDs@PCN-222 is attributed to the electrostatic attraction and large BET surface area of MOF, while the excellent adsorption of RhB by 2N-CDs@PCN-222@PNIPAM2 with a greatly reduced BET surface area should benefit from the improvement of its surface wettability of the photocatalyst by the PNIPAM to promote the enrichment of the RhB around the active site of catalyst. Compared with 2N-CDs@PCN-222, 2N-CDs@PCN-222@PNIPAM2 is degraded more rapidly after 5 min of light exposure, indicating that PNIPAM functionalized MOF not only gives the photocatalyst temperature switch capability, but also has higher photocatalytic performance. Therefore, hydrophilic PNIPAM and P(PEGMA) give the MOF surface significant wettability, which compensates for the reduction of the 2N-CDs@PCN-222@PNIPAM2 and 2N-CDs@PCN-222@P(PEGMA) BET surface area, and further improves the photocatalytic properties of photocatalysts, but PMMA as a hydrophobic polymer cannot achieve such a goal. We measured the contact angles of 2N-CDs@PCN-222@PNIPAM2, 2N-CDs@PCN-222@P(PEGMA) and 2N-CDs@PCN-222@PMMA to verify this conclusion (Fig. 8
                        ). The contact angles of 2N-CDs@PCN-222@PNIPAM2, 2N-CDs@PCN-222@P(PEGMA) and 2N-CDs@PCN-222@PMMA are 38°, 46° and 136° respectively, which means that 2N-CDs@PCN-222@PNIPAM2 and 2N-CDs@PCN-222@P(PEGMA) are hydrophilic photocatalysts, while 2N-CDs@PCN-222@PMMA is a hydrophobic photocatalyst. Thus, the catalytic performance of photocatalysts is not positively correlated with their specific surface area. Our result demonstrates that the introduction of hydrophilic polymers can regulate the hydrophilic environment around MOF catalytic active sites and promote the enrichment and transformation of hydrophilic substrates.
